 Basics

    Introduction

    https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/artificial-intelligence/artificial-intelligence/

    Concepts:
        1) Machine Learning:
                Identifies patterns and relationships from data to improve predictions and decisions through experience.Used for recommendation and Prediction
        
        2)Generative:
                Generates new content instead of only analyzing data from learning patterns from massive databases .Used in Chatbots, image generation and content writing tools.
        
        3) Natural Language Processing:
                Enables computers to understand and interpret human languages through translation , sentiment analysis and chatbots. Used for voice assistants 
        
        4)Expert Systems:
                Simulate human decision making and specific domain knowledge using if then rules to mimic reasoning of humans in specific domains. Used in healthcare finance and diagnostics
    
    Working:
        1)Data Collection:
            AI systems require large sets of data to learn etc
        
        2)Processing and Learning:
            Uses algorithms to analyze data and identify patterns
        
        3)Model Training:
            Trained using the data adjusting its settings to improve predictions . more data leads to more accurate and better at recognizing 
        
        4)Decision Making:
            Once trained ,can use what it learned to make decisions
        
        5)Feedback and Improvement:
            Models can be improved through feedback  such as reinforcement learning
    
    Types Of AI:
        Capability
            1)Narrow
                Designed for specific tasks such as recognition or recommendation
        
            2)General AI
                Theoretical AI capable of performing human like intelligence in multiple domains
        
            3) SuperIntelligent AI
                Hypothetical AI that surpasses human intelligence i reasoning and decision making
        
        Functionality
            1)Reactive Machines
                systems that respond only to current inputs without storing other experiences
            
            2)Limited Memory
                use past data and observations to improve future decisions
            
            3)Theory of Mind
                theoretical AI that could understand human emotions beliefs and intentions
            
            4)Self Aware
                Hypothetical AI with consciousness and awareness of its own existence
            
    AI Models:
        1)Supervised
            Training is based on labeled data with clear input output pairs to learn relationships reducing prediction errors
        
        2)Unsupervised
            works with unlabeled data to identify hidden patterns and trends automatically , discovering structures within databases
        
        3)Reinforcement Learning Models
            AI learns by interacting with an environment using rewards and penalties as feedback.Optomising decisions through trial and error
    
Agents:
    Agents operate with a degree of autonomy to completeassigned tasks effectively
    
    Features
        1)Autonomous
            Act without constant human input and decide next steps using past data
            
        2)Goal Driven
            optomise for defined objectives

        3)Perceptive
            gather info from sensors , inputs or APIs 
            
        4)Adaptable
            Adjust strategies when situations change
            
        5)Collaborative
            works with hymans or other agents toward shared goals

    Classification:
        1)Reactive
            respond to stimulo without foresight or planning
            
        2)Proactive
            Anticipate future states and plan actions to achieve long term goals
        
        3)Single Agent
            one agent to solve a problem independently
        
         4)Multi Agent
            multiple agents interact coordinate or compete to achieve goals
            
        5)Rational Agents
            Choose actions to maximize expected outcomes
    
    Types:
        1)Simple Reflex
            reacts immediately to inputs without consideration.excel in predictable environments.can react without delay but cannot learn

        2)Model-Based Reflex
            improve simplex reflex agents by maintaining an internal state of the environment to handle partially observable and changing situations

        3)Goal Based 
        Choose actions by evaluating future states in relation to defined goals

        4)Utility Based
            evaluate how desirable different outcomes are using a utility function.This allows them to choose the most optimal action in uncertain or limited recource situations

        5)Learning
            imrpove performance over time by learning from experience and updateing thier models/strategies

        6)Multi Agent System (MAS)
            involves multiple agents interacting in a shared environment to achieve individual or collective goals

        7)Hierarchical
            structure behaviour into layers such as strategic tactical and operational.
    
Problem Solving:
    Search Algorithms:
        Used to locate specific items within a collection of data
    
        Common Searches:
            1)Linear Search
                iterate through the data sequentially to find the data
            
            2)Binary Search
                used on a sorted array , compares the middle element first and then removes the half of the list based on the comparison result
        
        Breadth First Search:
            For graph traversal Breadth first traversal starts on a source node and explores a graph level by level, only going down once each node away from the previous node has been checked for n nodes away from the source
        
        Depth First Search:
            Traverse all adjacent vertices one by once reaching a vertex we finish the traversal of all vertices reachable from that vertex
        
        Uniform Cost Search:
            an uninformed search algorithm used to find the lowest cost path between a start node and a goal node in a weighted graph.it systematically explores paths based on the cumulative cost ,used for cost sensitive pathfinding problems

            Concepts:
                1)Priority Queue
                    used to store nodes selecting the node with lowest weight
                
                2)Path Cost
                    Calculates cumulative cost from the start node to the current node,prioritizing nodes with lower costs
                
                3)Node Expansion
                    Explores nodes in order of increasing path cost

                4)Optimal Solution
                    stops when the goal node is reached through the lowest cost path
        
        Bidirectional Search:
            start search from the source and goal node simultaneously
        
        Greedy Best First Search:
            selects a path that appears most promising at each step.uses heuristic values to guide the search toward the goal efficiently.prioritizes fast exploration over guaranteed optimal solution.
            
            Working:
                Evaluates each node using heuristic values selecting the lowest heuristic value for expansion
                Expands the most promising path instead of exploring all possible paths
                Repeats process until the goal node is reached
                Uses heuristic estimates to reduce search time and guide traversal efficiently
        
            Limitations:
                1)does not guarrantee shortest path or most optimal solution

                2)Can get trapped in local optima

                3)Requires a suitable heuristic function,can increase complexity

                4)May fail in highly complex or cyclec search spaces without additional handling mechanisms
    
    Local Search Algorithms:
        optimisation techniques that improve a solution by repeatedly moving to a better neighbouring state instead of exploring every path

        Terminologies:
            1)State - a possible solution

            2)Current State - solution currently being evaluated

            3)Neighbour State - A solutioni formed by making small changes to the current state

            4)Objective state - A function used to measure the quality of a solution 

            5)Local Optimum - best solution among nearby states

            6)Global Optimum - best possible solution in the entire search space
        
        Working:
            1)Initial state selected , often random or based on a rule

            2) Find the neighbours, are similar solutions by making small changes to the current state

            3)Compare the neighbours to see if any are better than current state

            4)Move if a better neighbour exists

            5)keep searching from the new point until no neighbours are a better state
        
        Hill Climbing Search:
            a simple search algorithm that continuously moves toward a better neighboring solution until no solution is possible

        Simulated Annealing:
            ocassionally accepts worse solutions to escape local optima with the acceptance probability decreasing over time
            selects worse solutions based on decreasing probability

        Genetic Algorithms:
            work with a population of solutions and evolve them over time using genetic operators like selection crossover and mutation

        Tabu Search:
            uses a memory structure called the tabu list to avoid resisting previously explored solutions to prevent cycling back to local optima
        
        Beam Search:
            explores large search spaces by selecting only the most promising nodes at each level instead of expanding every possible path 

            Limitations:
                May miss the optimal solution if some paths are discrarded in early levels
                performance dependant on quality if function
                small beam width can remove potentially useful solutions
                Large beam width increases computation time 
    
    Adversial Search:
        when two or more agents have conflicting goals. adversial search can be used in two player sero sum games.Means  whats good for one player is bad for another no win win.used for competitive environments

        Used for:
            1)each agent boosts their own utility or minimize their loss

            2)One agents actions impacts the outcomes and objectives of other agents

            3)Strategic uncertainty arises when the agents may lack sufficient information
        
        Minimax:
            a recursive or backtracking algorithm responsible for choosing the best move in the conflicting environment.uses a game tree structure

            leaf nodes accomodate all possible moves game state denotes the current board conditions with every move

            algorithm proceeds down the tree until it reaches a leaf node then goes back as recursion unwinds.prime motive of the minimax algorithm is to maximize the chance of winning.higher weights lead to higher chances of winning

            1) Minimax Tree
                tree structure shows all possible moves and game states in a game
            
            2)MAX
                seeks favourable outcomes in games by maximizing their chance of winning
            
            3)Min
                reduces winning chances making moves leading to least favourable outcomes
            
            4)Initial state
                Starting state of game board representing configuration at beginning of the game

            5)Terminal state
                final outcomes of a game board resulting in win loss or draw
            
            6)Heuristic evaluation Function
                evaluates a game state for the maximizer assigning numerical values to each state based on peice positions
        
        Alpha beta pruning:
            optimization for minimax reducing computation time
            Max Value(state,alpha,beta)

            alpha:
                denotes the value of the best or highest value
            
            beta:
                denotes the value of the best or lowest value

            1)Branch elimination:
                the alpha beta pruning algorithm relies on the branches of the game tree that can be eliminates which promotes more promising subtrees (eliminate bad sections)
            
            2)Branch and bound:
                branch and bound which offers a way to solve the optimisation problem by dividing them into sub problems
            
            3)Heuristic improvements:
                to limit computation time, the heuristic alpha beta tree search cuts off the search early and applies the heuristic evaluation function
    
    Constraint Propogation:
        technique used to solve CSPs Constraint satisfaction Problems reducing the possible values of variables using constraints to narrow the search space

        eliminate invalid values from variable domains
        Reduces complexity of csps

        Concepts:
            1)Variables
                variables represent the unknowns in a problem
            
            2)Domains
                set of all possible valuse that can be assigned to a variable.Constraint propogation reduces these domains by removing values that violate constraints
            
            3)Constraints
                rules that define valid relationships between variables and restrict unacceptable value combinations
    
    Backtracking Search and its role:
        a depth first search algorithm that builds a solution by trying possible assignments
        abbandons a possible solution if it determines it cannot lead to the final solution 
        

        



        


            















